<i> - For the heat treat,</i>

11:28.730 --> 11:29.729
<i> I'm just gonna go</i>
<i> with my standard</i>

11:29.773 --> 11:31.106
<i> normalize quench.</i>

11:31.149 --> 11:33.483
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:33.527 --> 11:35.777
<i> The trick to normalizing</i>
<i> is making absolutely sure</i>

11:35.821 --> 11:40.365
<i> that you go from hot</i>
<i> to cold several times.</i>

11:40.409 --> 11:42.409
Got to wait for it to cool
completely to black,

11:42.452 --> 11:44.953
or if I dunk it in water,
it'll seize up and crack.

11:44.996 --> 11:46.830
<i> I'm using the shadows</i>
<i> here in the Forge</i>

11:46.873 --> 11:48.456
underneath the tables and tools

11:48.500 --> 11:50.250
just to make absolutely sure
that my blade is getting

11:50.293 --> 11:53.044
<i> to dead cold black.</i>

11:53.088 --> 11:55.296
If I don't get this
100% right,

11:55.340 --> 11:57.674
<i> the knife could be soft,</i>
<i> the knife could be too hard,</i>

11:57.718 --> 11:58.925
<i> and I could be screwed.</i>

11:58.969 --> 12:00.343
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:00.387 --> 12:01.928
- We should have
a quench coming up here.

12:01.972 --> 12:03.138
in just a minute with Sam.

12:03.181 --> 12:06.474
He's right on the edge.

12:06.518 --> 12:07.600
- Ready?

12:07.644 --> 12:09.310
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:09.354 --> 12:12.522
[exhales deeply]

12:12.566 --> 12:19.529
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:19.573 --> 12:22.198
Yes!
Whoo!

12:22.242 --> 12:23.700
- I felt excited
for him, too.

12:23.744 --> 12:25.410
I almost started clapping.
- Look at that.

12:25.454 --> 12:27.704
You got that
gorgeous hardness line.

12:27.748 --> 12:29.789
Aw, yes!

12:29.833 --> 12:32.375
- You have 15 minutes remaining
to finish your work!

12:32.419 --> 12:33.835
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:33.879 --> 12:35.587
Jon has made a hell
of a comeback.

12:35.630 --> 12:37.255
He's kept his cool.

12:37.299 --> 12:39.174
But he hasn't gone

12:39.217 --> 12:42.802
to any of the smaller contact
wheels to clean that fuller.

12:42.846 --> 12:44.763
<i> - All I need is 15 minutes</i>
<i> to reliably make sure</i>

12:44.806 --> 12:47.015
<i> that I have a quench.</i>

12:47.058 --> 12:48.433
<i> If I don't get</i>
<i> the heat treat right,</i>

12:48.477 --> 12:50.143
it might bend,
it might break.

12:50.187 --> 12:52.103
I made it thick.

12:52.147 --> 12:53.938
<i> I'm hoping it'll stand up</i>
<i> to what they do.</i>

12:53.982 --> 12:59.194
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:59.237 --> 13:00.987
- Ten, nine,

13:01.031 --> 13:04.199
eight, seven, six,

13:04.242 --> 13:06.743
five, four, three,

13:06.787 --> 13:09.412
two, one!

13:09.456 --> 13:11.456
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines!

13:11.500 --> 13:12.457
Drop your tools!

13:12.501 --> 13:16.836
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:16.880 --> 13:18.546
- This knife
is called conquest

13:18.590 --> 13:22.425
because I look to my left
and my right...

13:22.469 --> 13:23.802
and I've dominated.

13:23.845 --> 13:27.096
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:27.140 --> 13:29.641
- Bladesmiths,
your first-round challenge

13:29.684 --> 13:32.685
was to forge signature blades
using those backhoe buckets.

13:32.729 --> 13:34.687
Now it's time
for the judges to take

13:34.731 --> 13:36.898
a closer look
at your work.

13:36.942 --> 13:38.441
Keith, you're up first.

13:38.485 --> 13:40.151
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:40.195 --> 13:43.071
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

13:43.114 --> 13:45.073
- When you were working
with your steel,

13:45.116 --> 13:46.866
and you had it in the press,

13:46.910 --> 13:49.744
you kind of got
that taco thing happening.

13:49.788 --> 13:52.789
And it looks like some of that
stayed right in there.

13:52.833 --> 13:54.749
I mean, I can't really get
a fingernail in it,

13:54.793 --> 13:57.085
so it looks like
it's closed up pretty good.

13:57.128 --> 13:58.837
It does feel good
in the hand.

13:58.880 --> 14:00.713
Good job.

14:00.757 --> 14:02.257
- Sam, you're up next.

14:02.300 --> 14:04.092
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:04.135 --> 14:06.219
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:06.263 --> 14:08.137
<i> - Nice shape for a chopper.</i>

14:08.181 --> 14:09.430
It's very thick,
but you know what?

14:09.474 --> 14:11.641
Because of
the questionable steel,

14:11.685 --> 14:13.810
that might work
in your favor.

14:13.854 --> 14:17.313
It's heavy,
but I like the design.

14:17.357 --> 14:19.148
Good job.
- Thank you.

14:19.192 --> 14:20.817
- Riley, you're up next.

14:20.861 --> 14:23.653
<i> ♪</i> ♪

14:23.697 --> 14:25.405
- Think of it as
the feather knife.

14:25.448 --> 14:27.198
Looks like a turkey feather.

14:27.242 --> 14:28.908
Very thin.

14:28.952 --> 14:31.327
You had more steel
than this, didn't you?

14:31.371 --> 14:33.204
- No.
- You had a small piece, okay.

14:33.248 --> 14:34.998
- Yeah.

14:35.041 --> 14:38.543
- That is
exactly 10 inches.

14:38.587 --> 14:40.712
Depending on what we were
slicing or cutting,

14:40.755 --> 14:43.631
it could be a very, very
effective cutter.

14:43.675 --> 14:44.966
Good job.

14:45.010 --> 14:46.259
- Jon, you're up last.

14:46.303 --> 14:49.304
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:49.347 --> 14:51.764
<i> - Jon, I like the seax shape.</i>

14:51.808 --> 14:55.435
Before they were bowies,
we had seax.

14:55.478 --> 14:58.229
I see you started to kind of go
with a fuller in there.

14:58.273 --> 15:00.773
It's very rough, still.

15:00.817 --> 15:02.233
<i> If you make it</i>
<i> to the second round,</i>

15:02.277 --> 15:06.112
you'll possibly
do something about that.

15:06.156 --> 15:07.822
- Well, gentlemen,
I'm gonna ask you

15:07.866 --> 15:09.824
to leave your weapons
on this table and step away

15:09.868 --> 15:11.576
while the judges deliberate
which of you

15:11.620 --> 15:13.369
moves on to round two

15:13.413 --> 15:14.954
and who has to leave
the Forge.

15:14.998 --> 15:16.831
Thank you.

15:16.875 --> 15:21.711
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

15:21.755 --> 15:23.713
- This is gonna
be interesting.

15:23.757 --> 15:25.715
- Anybody else shaking harder
than they've ever shook before?

15:25.759 --> 15:27.258
- Yeah.

15:27.302 --> 15:29.135
- All right, judges,
let's go ahead

15:29.179 --> 15:32.263
and discuss each blade's
strengths and weaknesses.

15:32.307 --> 15:34.182
We'll start with Keith's,
on the end.

15:34.225 --> 15:37.268
<i> - Very interesting design</i>
<i> that Keith presented us.</i>

15:37.312 --> 15:38.686
<i> You've got a point here</i>

15:38.730 --> 15:40.063
that definitely lends
you to thinking

15:40.106 --> 15:41.522
it's going to be thrusting.

15:41.566 --> 15:43.566
We are doing testing
on chopping,

15:43.610 --> 15:45.485
and the widest part,
where you're gonna be

15:45.528 --> 15:47.862
trying to do most
of the effective chopping,

15:47.906 --> 15:49.697
is very close to the handle.

15:49.741 --> 15:51.866
Ideally, you want it to be
in the middle of the blade

15:51.910 --> 15:53.534
or at the tip
so it's more accurate

15:53.578 --> 15:55.995
when you're doing your chops.

15:56.039 --> 15:58.081
- All right, let's move on
to Sam's blade.

15:58.124 --> 16:00.708
<i>What do you think?</i>

16:00.752 --> 16:02.835
<i> - I like the blade profile.</i>

16:02.879 --> 16:05.421
<i> It's similar to what he drew.</i>

16:05.465 --> 16:08.424
Yet it is very thick.

16:08.468 --> 16:11.219
The handle is a little too long
and too skinny,

16:11.262 --> 16:13.179
but it was interesting
to watch him.

16:13.223 --> 16:15.473
He was having a lot of fun.

16:15.517 --> 16:17.684
- Let's take a look
at Riley's blade.

16:17.727 --> 16:19.102
Dave.
- The turkey feather,

16:19.145 --> 16:21.646
as he called it.
- The turkey feather.

16:21.690 --> 16:25.274
-<i> Riley pushed through.</i>
<i> He beat this thing flat.</i>

16:25.318 --> 16:28.152
He was having some issues
out there, you could tell.

16:28.196 --> 16:30.488
The problem is,
anything this thin

16:30.532 --> 16:33.616
on anything outside
of a kitchen knife,

16:33.660 --> 16:36.869
it'll work,
but it's just not supported.

16:36.913 --> 16:40.123
<i>- So let's move on</i>
<i>to Jon's blade.</i>

16:40.166 --> 16:43.334
<i> - This blade is pretty seax-y</i>
<i> in its profile.</i>

16:43.378 --> 16:45.336
<i> Everything else</i>
<i> is pretty lumpy.</i>

16:45.380 --> 16:47.714
Looks like it was ground
on highway.

16:47.757 --> 16:49.716
[imitates grinding]
Like I was hanging out the car,

16:49.759 --> 16:51.259
grinding like that.
- [laughs]

16:51.302 --> 16:52.552
- Yeah, I mean, it has
the roughest grind

16:52.595 --> 16:54.262
<i> of all the blades.</i>

16:54.305 --> 16:56.681
<i> It needs a lot of work.</i>

16:56.725 --> 16:59.017
- Judges, all these things taken
into consideration,

16:59.060 --> 17:01.644
it's time for you to decide
which of our smiths

17:01.688 --> 17:03.146
is leaving the Forge.

17:03.189 --> 17:04.981
Have you made
your final decision?

17:05.025 --> 17:07.108
- Yeah.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

17:07.152 --> 17:12.905
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:12.949 --> 17:14.240
All right, bladesmiths,

17:14.284 --> 17:16.367
the judges have examined
your work,

17:16.411 --> 17:18.578
and they've made
a final decision.

17:18.621 --> 17:20.997
It's time for one of you
to surrender his weapon

17:21.041 --> 17:22.665
and leave the Forge.

17:22.709 --> 17:24.542
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:24.586 --> 17:27.587
Riley, your blade
did not make the cut.

17:27.630 --> 17:29.547
- Riley, this was one
of our tougher challenges.

17:29.591 --> 17:31.758
- Yeah.
- But the problem is,

17:31.801 --> 17:35.428
it being so thin,
it's just not executed

17:35.472 --> 17:38.347
in a way that's gonna hold up
to our chop-and-slice tests.

17:38.391 --> 17:39.724
And that's why
we got to let you go.

17:39.768 --> 17:41.225
- Okay.

17:41.269 --> 17:43.311
- Riley, please surrender
your weapon.

17:43.354 --> 17:48.691
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:48.735 --> 17:51.027
<i> - I wish I had taken more</i>
<i> out of the bucket.</i>

17:51.071 --> 17:52.195
I didn't cut off
enough material,

17:52.238 --> 17:53.571
so I had to draw it out

17:53.615 --> 17:55.573
<i> and that made it</i>
<i> just too thin.</i>

17:55.617 --> 17:58.284
<i> I came in here</i>
<i> as a punk-rock blacksmith.</i>

17:58.328 --> 18:01.412
And I'm leaving here
as a punk-rock blacksmith,

18:01.456 --> 18:03.039
just with a little more
drive in me.

18:03.083 --> 18:07.085
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:07.128 --> 18:10.421
- Gentlemen,
this is round two.

18:10.465 --> 18:12.840
In this round, you'll be
attaching handles to your blades

18:12.884 --> 18:14.926
to turn them into
fully functioning weapons.

18:14.969 --> 18:16.594
It will then be tested
for sharpness,

18:16.638 --> 18:18.262
cutting through
a cargo strap,

18:18.306 --> 18:19.806
and for
strength and durability

18:19.849 --> 18:22.183
by chopping
into a construction barrier.

18:22.227 --> 18:23.935
Keeping with
our construction theme,

18:23.978 --> 18:25.603
you must also incorporate

18:25.647 --> 18:28.856
one of these construction
materials visually

18:28.900 --> 18:30.900
into your handle's
overall design.

18:30.944 --> 18:32.777
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:32.821 --> 18:35.613
When the time runs out
and the tests are complete,

18:35.657 --> 18:38.074
one of you will have
to surrender his weapon

18:38.118 --> 18:39.951
and leave the Forge.

18:39.994 --> 18:41.160
Any questions?

18:41.204 --> 18:42.453
All right, gentlemen,

18:42.497 --> 18:45.164
your three-hour time
starts...

18:45.208 --> 18:46.165
now.

18:46.209 --> 18:49.168
<i> ♪</i> ♪

18:49.212 --> 18:52.255
Anything you'd use
in a blade over there?

18:52.298 --> 18:54.215
- Probably would have gone
for that stop sign.

18:54.259 --> 18:57.677
We have all these amazing
handle materials.

18:57.720 --> 19:01.222
They can make accents out of
the reflective, shiny bits

19:01.266 --> 19:04.100
and use handle material
that we know is gonna hold up.

19:04.144 --> 19:05.560
- Hmm.

19:05.603 --> 19:06.853
<i> The barricade draws my eye</i>

19:06.896 --> 19:08.062
<i> because it's very flat</i>

19:08.106 --> 19:09.814
and it's white.

19:09.858 --> 19:14.152
<i> Now, white underneath anything</i>
<i> will always pop.</i>

19:14.195 --> 19:15.778
<i> ♪</i> ♪

19:15.822 --> 19:16.737
- There you go.

19:16.781 --> 19:21.033
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

19:21.077 --> 19:22.076
- Get it.

19:22.120 --> 19:24.996
Bite it.

19:25.039 --> 19:27.415
- I probably would have used
the chop saw, but--

19:27.458 --> 19:29.542
- [sighs]
- See, here we go.

19:29.586 --> 19:31.878
This is the way a gentlemen
with a gray beard does things.

19:31.921 --> 19:34.213
- That's right.
- [laughs]

19:34.257 --> 19:36.591
<i> - I decided to go</i>
<i> with the white plastic legs</i>

19:36.634 --> 19:41.721
from the road barricade
for the scales on the tang.

19:41.764 --> 19:44.015
- Keith, pretty much doing
the same thing as Sam is.

19:44.058 --> 19:46.517
He's got the plastic
from the sawhorse.

19:46.561 --> 19:49.270
- I think they're both using
them just to make liner.

19:49.314 --> 19:51.439
- How much time
does each of these smiths need

19:51.482 --> 19:53.232
to work on their blade?

19:53.276 --> 19:55.109
- Jon has the most.

19:55.153 --> 19:58.070
- I need to enhance this fuller,
make it look better,

19:58.114 --> 20:00.031
make it a little more even
on both sides

20:00.074 --> 20:02.074
so it looks beautiful
for the judges.

20:02.118 --> 20:05.703
- [laughs]
- That was cool.

20:05.747 --> 20:07.705
- I decided to use
some blue and gold kirinite

20:07.749 --> 20:10.666
<i> to go over the white liners</i>
<i> from the barricade.</i>

20:10.710 --> 20:12.168
<i> All the holes</i>
<i> are drilled properly.</i>

20:12.212 --> 20:14.045
<i> Everything's flat.</i>

20:14.088 --> 20:15.880
<i> Now all I have to do</i>
<i> is make sure the pins fit.</i>

20:15.924 --> 20:21.385
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:21.429 --> 20:22.720
Aw, man!

20:22.764 --> 20:25.223
- Oh, we hate the "oh, man."

20:25.266 --> 20:27.808
- That blows.

20:27.852 --> 20:28.809
[bleep].

20:28.853 --> 20:31.187
There's a crack.

20:31.231 --> 20:32.396
Double [bleep].

20:32.440 --> 20:34.398
There's another crack.

20:34.442 --> 20:36.651
[whistles]
Already an hour and a half in.

20:36.694 --> 20:39.570
- Sam is nearing
that point of no return.

20:39.614 --> 20:41.572
- I don't know
if anybody heard the thump,

20:41.616 --> 20:43.908
but that was my heart
hitting the sole of my boots.

20:43.952 --> 20:45.534
Kirinite, ladies and gentlemen.

20:45.578 --> 20:46.786
[bleep].

20:46.829 --> 20:48.120
<i> I'm finished.</i>

20:48.164 --> 20:51.332
♪ ♪

20:54.921 --> 20:57.630
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:57.674 --> 21:01.050
- So it looks like Sam's
kirinite scales have broken.

21:01.094 --> 21:03.594
Is this a good time for him
to abandon this process

21:03.638 --> 21:05.263
and go with something else?
- Yeah.

21:05.306 --> 21:08.057
- There's cracks
in this kirinite.

21:08.101 --> 21:10.476
I'm a little bit gun-shy
about using kirinite again.

21:10.520 --> 21:12.061
<i> It's just brittle material,</i>

21:12.105 --> 21:14.730
and I like to lock my pins down
with a hammer.

21:14.774 --> 21:17.984
I chose a slightly
tougher material--micarta.

21:18.027 --> 21:20.444
And I'm doing
the exact same steps.

21:20.488 --> 21:22.571
<i> If I'm gonna show</i>
<i> the world what I've got,</i>

21:22.615 --> 21:25.074
I got to make sure that I'm
starting with good stuff.

21:25.118 --> 21:27.743
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:27.787 --> 21:30.413
- I can't really tell
what Keith has going on here.

21:30.456 --> 21:32.790
- The different layers
on the handle are

21:32.834 --> 21:34.583
<i> epoxy, micarta,</i>

21:34.627 --> 21:36.002
and then I have
the road barricade.

21:36.045 --> 21:37.878
Ha ha.

21:37.922 --> 21:40.548
- I think Keith is actually
making a booby trap over there

21:40.591 --> 21:43.801
with a lot of
pins and nuts and bolts

21:43.845 --> 21:45.720
and projectiles in there.

21:45.763 --> 21:47.388
- I'm a messy man.

21:47.432 --> 21:49.890
- You have only
60 minutes remaining.

21:49.934 --> 21:53.436
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

21:53.479 --> 21:55.104
<i> - The stop sign is the perfect</i>
<i> piece to use</i>

21:55.148 --> 21:56.272
<i> for the guard</i>
<i> and the butt cap</i>

21:56.316 --> 21:57.565
<i> because they're both the end.</i>

21:57.608 --> 22:00.192
And we stop at the end.

22:00.236 --> 22:02.194
<i> The aluminum isn't really,</i>
<i> really beautiful,</i>

22:02.238 --> 22:04.238
<i> but I'll let the reflective</i>
<i> surface of the stop sign</i>

22:04.282 --> 22:05.614
<i> speak for itself.</i>

22:08.369 --> 22:09.785
I'm over at the pantry.

22:09.829 --> 22:11.162
<i> In the back,</i>
<i> I spot a nice piece</i>

22:11.205 --> 22:12.788
<i> of used hammer handle.</i>

22:12.832 --> 22:14.540
All my knives
are meant to be tough

22:14.584 --> 22:16.459
and survive anything
you put at them.

22:16.502 --> 22:18.419
<i> I know the hammer handle</i>
<i> will do that job,</i>

22:18.463 --> 22:20.880
and that's
what I'm working for.

22:20.923 --> 22:22.006
[metal clanging]

22:22.050 --> 22:24.550
- Sorry, big guy.

22:24.594 --> 22:26.302
<i> The handle material</i>
<i> has been swapped out,</i>

22:26.346 --> 22:28.512
The epoxy has dried,
and my pins are set.

22:28.556 --> 22:29.930
<i> Now I'm gonna march over</i>
<i> to the grinder</i>

22:29.974 --> 22:31.307
<i> and start taking away</i>
<i> material.</i>

22:31.351 --> 22:32.725
The gods have been
good today.

22:32.769 --> 22:33.893
- Yeah, man.

22:33.936 --> 22:35.394
- I'm just moving very carefully

22:35.438 --> 22:37.605
and making sure
not to take off too much.

22:37.648 --> 22:41.025
I just want a person to smile
when they touch it.

22:41.069 --> 22:43.903
- Man, that handle is thick.
Look at that thing.

22:43.946 --> 22:48.074
- Keith's handle doesn't look
any thinner than Sam's.

22:48.117 --> 22:49.492
- The most crucial thing
that I get right

22:49.535 --> 22:51.202
<i> is shaping the handle</i>

22:51.245 --> 22:53.245
so it has a good,
strong grip on it

22:53.289 --> 22:55.331
<i> and it's not going to slip</i>
<i> out of their hands.</i>

22:55.375 --> 22:56.957
- Look how much
Keith is battling

22:57.001 --> 22:58.793
with that plastic.

22:58.836 --> 23:01.754
- The plastic is kind of rolling
over and melting.

23:01.798 --> 23:04.173
It's not really allowing me
to grind as hard

23:04.217 --> 23:06.425
as I really would want to.

23:06.469 --> 23:09.178
